  and $1/2+x/(2t)$ is increasing, so it must peak at exactly $x = 1 - t$. Hence,
  $ chi^*_([0, 1]) (x) = 1 / (2(1-x)). $
  Similarly, for all $x >= 1$, by symmetry, we have:
  $ chi^*_([0, 1]) (x) = 1 / (2x). $
]

